Viola nuttallii is a species of flowering plant native to North America. 
It is commonly known as Nuttall's violet.
The plant displays small, delicate flowers in shades of purple, with yellow centers.
Each flower has five petals, two of which are slightly larger than the other three.
The foliage is heart-shaped with serrated edges, and has a smooth texture.
Viola nuttallii is commonly found in rocky, mountainous areas, and can also thrive in meadows and forests.
The plant is known to attract a variety of pollinators, such as bees and butterflies.
